From 0000000000000000000000000000000000000000 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: nix-on-z <nix-on-z@s390x>
Date: Thu, 10 Apr 2026 00:00:00 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] Fix Parquet native reader endianness for big-endian platforms

Parquet format stores all multi-byte integers in little-endian byte order.
The native Parquet reader (V3) uses memcpy and unalignedLoad to read these
values, which produces native byte order -- correct on x86 (little-endian)
but wrong on s390x (big-endian).

Fix all sites to use explicit little-endian conversion via a fromLittleEndian()
helper that compiles to a no-op on little-endian platforms:

Reader.cpp (4 sites):
- Footer metadata size (memcpy of 4-byte LE int32)
- DATA_PAGE_V1 rep/def level byte lengths (2x memcpy of 4-byte LE uint32)
- Bloom filter word reads (unalignedLoad of LE uint32)

Decoding.cpp (21 sites):
- RLE length prefix (memcpy of 4-byte LE uint32)
- RLE run values (memcpy of variable-width LE int)
- Bit-packed 8-byte reads (memcpy of LE uint64 for bit extraction)
- String length prefixes (5x memcpy of 4-byte LE uint32)
- Dictionary page string lengths (memcpy of 4-byte LE uint32)
- Dictionary fixed-size index fast-path (raw memcpy of LE column values, v3)
- memcpyIntoColumn plain fixed-size column data fast-path (v3)
- Integer column conversion (memcpy of LE integers)
- Integer statistics (unalignedLoad of LE uint16/32/64)
- Float statistics (memcpy of LE float32/64)
- Float16 conversion (memcpy of LE uint16)
- INT96 timestamps (unalignedLoad of LE int64 + int32)
- ByteStreamSplit 8-byte reads (unalignedLoad of LE uint64)

On little-endian (x86): fromLittleEndian() is a compile-time no-op via
if-constexpr, producing identical generated code to the original.

On big-endian (s390x): each site adds one LRVG/LRVR (Load Reversed)
instruction, which executes in a single cycle on z15.
